scribes the primary molecular defect in cystic fibrosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Defective chloride channel protein","Defective sodium channel protein","Defective potassium channel protein","Defective bicarbonate transport","Defective mucin production"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary defect in cystic fibrosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Edefective chloride channel protein\u003C/strong\u003E called the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR). Mutations in the CFTR gene lead to absent or dysfunctional chloride channels, particularly affecting epithelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective sodium channel protein\u003C/strong\u003E - While sodium transport is secondarily affected, the primary defect involves chloride channels\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective mucin production\u003C/strong\u003E - Mucin production itself is normal; the thick mucus results from abnormal ion transport\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective bicarbonate transport\u003C/strong\u003E - While bicarbonate transport is affected, this is secondary to the chloride channel defect\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective potassium channel protein\u003C/strong\u003E - Potassium channels are not primarily involved in cystic fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe defective chloride transport leads to altered fluid secretion across epithelial surfaces, resulting in thick, sticky mucus that affects multiple organ systems including the lungs, pancreas, and reproductive tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cystic fibrosis is caused by mutations in the CFTR gene which codes for a chloride channel protein.","The most common mutation in cystic fibrosis is F508del which causes protein misfolding and degradation.","CFTR dysfunction leads to thick mucus secretions affecting multiple organ systems."],"references":["Sharma N, Cutting GR. The genetics and genomics of cystic fibrosis. J Cyst Fibros. 2020 Mar;19 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S5-S9. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8008819/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55037"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17254"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55037"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:08:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:09:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9944"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69585"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":